Quoting Willie McKemie <wmckemie2@gmail.com>:

> On Sun, Oct 21, 2012 at 07:56:31PM -0600, eric@ericwichman.com wrote:
>> Is there an EV that any of you would consider driving cross country
>> long distance?
>>
>> Conversion is ok as long as it's reliable. A manufactured American
>> made vehicle would be ideal.
>
> My experience (I am also considering some long distance EV travel):
> 1) A conversion may not be reliable until it has been shaken out for a
> year or two.=A0 My Hyundai went through two very un-reliable years but is
> now quite reliable.
> 2) The bigger the pack you have, the fewer "fuel" stops you will need.
> I consider my 40kwh pack about as big as is practical.=A0 That gives me
> 150+ miles, but only 120 anxiety free miles.=A0 That is, I start
> looking for a charge after 100 miles.=A0 The replacement cost on a 40kwh
> pack is now about $15k.
> 3) Your best charging resource is RV parks.=A0 You will minimize your
> charge time by matching your charger to the 50amp @ 240vac available in
> RV parks.=A0 About 10kw.=A0 Most silly J1772 stations will not supply that
> much power.=A0 I have found I can drive about 2 hours on a charge and
> then need about three hours to recharge.=A0 That is about the best you
> can hope to do without well positioned level 3 charging.=A0 That gives
> you about 100 miles in 5 hours or less than 500 miles per day even if
> you drive/charge around the clock.
>
> A $80k Tesla Model S seems very well suited to your project.=A0 With a
> 80kwh pack, it gives you almost a day's driving on one charge and then
> can be charged almost anywhere, including RV parks, overnight.=A0 You may
> not get much more than 500 miles/day in a Tesla but you will have a
> nice long sleep period.
>
> http://www.evalbum.com/2314
